    <text>
    <body>
        
        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName>Down | Beckenham. Kent.</placeName>
                    <date>Ap 19<hi rend="superscript">th</hi>.</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. Balfour is in Naples &amp; I do not know his address,<ref target="#foot.f2"/> so that the circular does not signify. I was very glad to see that your great undertaking was progressing favourably.<ref target="#foot.f3"/> You must be reading one of the first Editions of the Origin, for I altered &amp; omitted long ago that part about the rate of the sea eating back the land, in which I blundered most egregiously<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>My dear Sir | Y<hi rend="superscript">rs</hi>. very faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_258.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Francis Maitland Balfour’s</ref> stay in Naples (see n. 2, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Balfour was in Naples in April 1874; he had been doing research at the Zoological Station there since late 1873 (see <ref target="./DCP-LETT-9396.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Michael Foster, 7 April [1874]</ref> and n. 2).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">No letter from Willett has been found; the circular may have involved the Wealden Exploration Fund, which Willett had established to support geological excavations of the Sussex Downs (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_8386.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">[Willett] 1878</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">CD refers to his revised discussion of the denudation of the Weald (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6015.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 2d ed.</ref>, p. 285, and <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_6016.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Origin</hi> 3d ed.</ref>, p. xii), which had important consequences for his estimates of geological time.</note>
        </div>        
            
